50|$|There {{was much}} action taken towards {{the repeal of}} the <b>Contagious</b> <b>Diseases</b> Acts. In 1869, the National Association for the Repeal of the <b>Contagious</b> <b>Diseases</b> Acts was established; {{initially}} restricting women from its meetings, causing the Ladies National Association for the Repeal of the <b>Contagious</b> <b>Diseases</b> Acts to be quickly established by Josephine Butler. These repeal organisations attracted the vigorous support of moralists and feminists but also those more generally concerned with civil liberties, especially since the Acts were perceived as having violated basic human rights.|$|R
